  "body": "I'm testing POSDAO features in Nethermind using our [`posdao-test-setup`](https://github.com/poanetwork/posdao-test-setup/tree/nethermind) tool and today discovered that commit/reveal phase starts with 1-block delay in comparison to OpenEthereum's behaviour (actually not, but I was initially confused looking to the logs).\r\n\r\nI attached two log files of the [`watcher.js`](https://github.com/poanetwork/posdao-test-setup/blob/nethermind/scripts/watcher.js) script output (see below): one for OpenEthereum and another for Nethermind. There are only first 50 blocks in the logs.\r\n\r\nIn OpenEthereum's logs we see that the watcher script detects `Block 19` as in the `COMMITS PHASE`, but Nethermind's logs show the same block as already `REVEALS PHASE`.\r\n\r\nThe same is observed for block 38: OpenEthereum shows it is in `REVEALS PHASE`, but Nethermind shows as the block in `COMMITS PHASE`.\r\n\r\nI guess, the reason is in [`isCommitPhase`](https://github.com/poanetwork/posdao-contracts/blob/229d6441ae32fd4250884e1c8d53f7fec10a9e9e/contracts/RandomAuRa.sol#L259-L261) getter which takes [`block.number`](https://github.com/poanetwork/posdao-contracts/blob/229d6441ae32fd4250884e1c8d53f7fec10a9e9e/contracts/RandomAuRa.sol#L366-L368) as a current block number. Seems for public getters Nethermind returns a future block number in the `block.number` instead of the latest one. I checked that with a separate small test and it confirmed my assumption.\r\n\r\nCould you make its behaviour the same as OpenEthereum's?\r\n\r\nPlease also check other `block.*` properties for Solidity: https://solidity.readthedocs.io/en/v0.5.10/units-and-global-variables.html?highlight=block.number#block-and-transaction-properties\r\n\r\nAttached logs:\r\n[watcher.nethermind.log](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/files/5028808/watcher.nethermind.log)\r\n[watcher.openethereum.log](https://github.com/NethermindEth/nethermind/files/5028810/watcher.openethereum.log)\r\n\r\n",
